    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-04-25T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-04-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="28"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d28">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/4093</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">
                        <persName type="from">Baron Rosen</persName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d28fn1">Russian Ambassador at Washington, 1905–11.</note>
                    <hi rend="italic">to President <persName corresp="#p_WW1" type="to"
                            >Wilson</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Petrograd</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-content-and-sibling-dates"
                            calendar="gregorian" when="1917-04-25">
                            <hi rend="italic">undated</hi>
                        </date>. <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received April 25, 1917, 6.29
                        a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Public meeting convened in Petrograd town hall by Society for Promoting Friendly
                    Relations between Russia and America.<note n="2" xml:id="d28fn2">For the account
                        by the Ambassador in Russia of the Russian-American meeting of Apr. 23 in
                        the hall of the City Duma at Petrograd, mainly devoted to denunciations of
                        the idea of a separate peace, see his telegram No. 1217, Apr. 24, 1917, <ref
                            target="frus1917Supp02v01">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1917, Supplement 2, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">i</hi>
                        </ref>.</note> After being addressed by American Ambassador and Foreign
                    Minister sends <pb facs="0107" n="33" xml:id="pg_33"/> to you and the American
                    people whom you represent in such noble way its fraternal greetings and
                    expression of admiration for your constant upholding of the great principles of
                    freedom and right. We are deeply convinced that our two countries which
                    represent the greatest democracies of the world will remain forever closely
                    united and work in common for the progress of humanity.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Baron Rosen</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                    <lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Chairman</hi>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
